  "output": "I'm restricted to the `apps/cli` working directory this session, so I'll analyze what's actually in scope: the Go TUI codebase. This is a small (~480 line), single-purpose Bubble Tea app with no database, no React, and no HTTP caching layer — so several checklist categories don't apply here. Here's what I found that's real.\n\n## Findings for `apps/cli`\n\n### 1. O(n²) log rebuild on every streamed line — `tui.go:245-252`\n\n```go\nfunc (m *model) refreshViewport() {\n\tname := m.highlighted()\n\tif name == \"\" {\n\t\treturn\n\t}\n\tm.vp.SetContent(strings.Join(m.statuses[name].lines, \"\\n\"))\n\tm.vp.GotoBottom()\n}\n```\n\nEvery `statusMsg` (one per stdout line from the crawler subprocess) triggers a full `strings.Join` over **all** accumulated lines for the highlighted provider — not just the new one. For a provider that streams N lines, that's O(1+2+...+N) = O(N²) string work over the run, and it reallocates the whole buffer each time. With `--limit 0` (\"run until exhausted\") this scales with total crawl output, which could be sizable per provider (scrapling logs are chatty).\n\n**Fix** — build the joined string incrementally instead of rejoining from scratch:\n\n```go\ntype providerStatus struct {\n\tstate   providerState\n\tlines   []string\n\tcontent strings.Builder // accumulated, newline-joined\n}\n\n// on new line:\nif st.content.Len() > 0 {\n\tst.content.WriteByte('\\n')\n}\nst.content.WriteString(msg.line)\n\n// refreshViewport:\nm.vp.SetContent(m.statuses[name].content.String())\nm.vp.GotoBottom()\n```\n\nThis drops the append cost to amortized O(1) per line instead of O(N) per line.\n\n### 2. `articlesSaved` rescans full history every render — `tui.go:360-368`, called from `viewRunning:398`\n\n```go\nfunc articlesSaved(lines []string) int {\n\tn := 0\n\tfor _, l := range lines {\n\t\tif strings.HasPrefix(l, \"  - \") {\n\t\t\tn++\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\treturn n\n}\n```\n\n`viewRunning()` calls this **once per provider, on every `View()`** — and `View()` fires on every message, including the spinner's `Tick` (~10/sec by default) while providers are still running. So for R running providers with L accumulated lines each, that's O(R·L) work roughly 10 times a second, purely to recompute a monotonically increasing counter.\n\n**Fix** — maintain a running counter instead of rescanning:\n\n```go\ntype providerStatus struct {\n\tstate   providerState\n\tlines   []string\n\tsavedCt int\n}\n\n// where a line is appended (Update, statusMsg case):\nst.lines = append(st.lines, msg.line)\nif strings.HasPrefix(msg.line, \"  - \") {\n\tst.savedCt++\n}\n```\n\nThen `viewRunning` just reads `st.savedCt` instead of calling `articlesSaved(st.lines)`.\n\n### 3. Unbounded memory growth — `providerStatus.lines`\n\n`st.lines = append(st.lines, msg.line)` (`tui.go:110`) never caps growth. With `--limit 0`, a chatty provider could accumulate an arbitrarily large slice held for the process lifetime. Not a leak (it's live-referenced, reachable, and needed for the \"history\" feature), but worth a bound if long unlimited runs are a real use case — e.g. cap `lines` at the last N entries with a ring buffer, or drop old lines once the viewport no longer needs full scrollback.\n\n### Not applicable here\n- **N+1 queries** — no database/ORM in this Go binary; it only shells out to a Python subprocess per provider.\n- **React re-renders** — this is a terminal UI (Bubble Tea), not React; the closest analogue (unnecessary `View()`/`refreshViewport()` work) is covered in #1–#2.\n- **Caching** — there's no repeated fetch/compute of the same external data to cache; each provider runs once per session.\n\nIf you want the N+1/caching/memory-leak analysis for the actual data-fetching layer, that logic lives in `apps/crawler` (Python — `base.py`, `main.py`, `models.py`, `providers.py`), which is outside this session's allowed working directory (`apps/cli`). Say the word and I'll start a new session scoped there, or you can grant access and I'll continue in this one.\n",
